Actually, [`array_search`][1] returns `false`, not `&#39;&#39;` if no match is found. As you point out, that is the same as 0 in a simple equality comparison ([`==` or `!=`][2]) because `false` can be [type juggled][3] to `0`, so you need to do a strict equality test ([`===` or `!==`][2]) which also takes into account the type of the operands. Since `false` is boolean and `0` is an integer, this check will fail. So write something like this:

    $key = array_search($value, $array);
    if ($key !== false) {
        // found
    }
    else {
        // not found
    }


  [1]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.array-search.php
  [2]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/language.operators.comparison.php
  [3]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/language.types.type-juggling.php

